    "content": "Mogadishu is actively pursuing bilateral security pacts with nations that have contributed troops to the African Union mission in Somalia, aiming to secure continued military support after the AU mandate ends in December 2026. Officials confirmed the talks, which would shift select foreign forces from the AU framework to direct agreements with Somalia's federal government.\n\nThe push for alternative security arrangements comes as the current AU stabilization mission approaches its conclusion. The Somali government is concerned about a security vacuum that could embolden militant groups like Al-Shabaab. Under the proposed bilateral deals, troop-contributing countries would maintain a presence in Somalia under terms negotiated directly with Mogadishu rather than through the AU.\n\nThe urgency has intensified following Washington's decision to halt financial backing for Somalia's security sector. The US has been a key funder of both the AU mission and Somali security forces, and the funding suspension has left a significant gap. For the Somali diaspora, these developments raise concerns about stability and the safety of family members and business interests back home.\n\nThe bilateral agreements are still under discussion, with no final details released. However, the shift represents a significant change in Somalia's security strategy, moving away from multilateral AU-led operations toward more direct partnerships. The coming months will be critical as the December deadline approaches.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Dalsan here: https://radiodalsan.com/2026/07/16/somalia-scrambles-for-new-military-allies-as-au-troops-face-exit/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=somalia-scrambles-for-new-military-allies-as-au-troops-face-exit",
