    "summary": "Fighting broke out late Wednesday in Baidoa after forces loyal to former Southwest State President Abdiazis Laftagaren attacked Somali National Army positions, including Turkish-trained Gorgor Special Forces bases.",
    "content": "Heavy fighting erupted late Wednesday night in Baidoa, the capital of Somalia's Southwest state, after militias loyal to former regional President Abdiazis Laftagaren launched an assault on positions held by the Somali National Army. The attack began from the northern outskirts of the city, targeting military bases occupied by the Turkish-trained Gorgor Special Forces and military police units. This triggered hours of intense combat across parts of Baidoa.\n\nThe clashes mark a significant escalation in tensions between Laftagaren, who was ousted from the presidency in 2023, and the federal government. Laftagaren has maintained a power base in the region, and his forces have previously resisted integration into the national army. The attack on SNA positions appears to be a direct challenge to federal authority in the Southwest state.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, Baidoa holds particular significance as the hub for humanitarian operations serving millions of internally displaced people. The renewed instability could disrupt aid delivery and further destabilize the region, which already faces threats from Al-Shabaab. Reports indicate that civilian movement has been restricted as fighting continued into the early morning hours.\n\nThe federal government has yet to issue an official statement, but the attack underscores ongoing challenges in consolidating security forces under a unified command. The role of Turkish-trained special forces highlights international engagement in Somalia's security sector, though their involvement in internal political disputes raises questions about the effectiveness of such partnerships.\n\nRead the original report from Somalia Guardian here: https://www.somaliguardian.com/news/somalia-news/heavy-fighting-baidoa-laftagaren-forces-attack-somali-army-positions/",
